AGI - In Florida the police published the images recorded by the bodycam of a vicesceriff documenting the killing by mistake, and in cold blood, of a 23-year-old African American aviour, who stood at home talking via Facetime with his fiancée. The victim is Roger Fortson, a U.S. Air Force Military, a boy who the family described as a "patriot who respected authority and hoped to buy one day to the mother and her younger brothers a home".
&nbsp;
Killing him was Okaloosa County Vicesceriff: After knocking twice at the door and claiming to be a member of the sheriff's office, the boy opened the door and, after just a second, the officer shot him six shots. While Fortson was on the ground wounded, the cop yelled at him "push the gun." The victim said, "I don't have it." There are no other images at the moment.
<
&nbsp;
</div
County Sheriff Eric Aden showed the short video during a press conference. Aden met the victim's family, but at the moment he didn't unbalance the dynamics of the tragedy. "What we know - he added - is that the vice-sceriffo had been identified not once, but two."
&nbsp;
"The words spoken by Fortson - he continued - indicate that he was aware of the fact that there were representatives of the law at the door and he presented himself with a gun in his hand. The vicesceriffo knocked at the door, didn't cover the spike or obscured the view in any way." But the aviator's family claims the sheriff's men went to the wrong address. "The police said in a written statement - went to the wrong apartment while Rogers was on the phone with his fiancée. There was no one else in the house."&nbsp;
